/*!
\page constants_eps EPS Double Precision Floating Point Relative Machine Precision Epsilon

<p>
Section: \ref sec_constants "Base Constants"
\section Usage
Returns <tt>eps</tt>, which quantifies the relative machine precision
of floating point numbers (a machine specific quantity).  The syntax
for <tt>eps</tt> is:
\verbatim
   y = eps
   y = eps('double')
   y = eps(X)
\endverbatim
First form returns <tt>eps</tt> for <tt>double</tt> precision values. For most
typical processors, this value is approximately <tt>2^-52</tt>, or 2.2204e-16.
Second form return <tt>eps</tt> for class <tt>double</tt> or <tt>single</tt>.
Third form returns distance to the next value greater than X.
\section Example
The following example demonstrates the use of the <tt>eps</tt> function,
and one of its numerical consequences.

\if FRAGMENT
frag_constants_eps_000.m
0
eps
1.0+eps
eps(1000.)
\endif


\verbinclude frag_constants_eps_000.m.out 

*/
